  "text": "In recent years, due to the illegal use of prohibited additives, improper use of veterinary drugs as well as overuse of medical drugs in production, use of livestock, poultry, and aquatic products, and residues of veterinary drugs, medical drugs, and prohibited additives have become some of the important factors affecting food safety. For example, tetracycline is widely used in livestock and poultry production as a broad-spectrum bacteriostatic agent. Due to the high dosage, long time, and abuse of the drug, it produces serious residues in animal muscle, milk, liver, and other foods, thereby endangering food safety [CITATION_1] . Based on high selectivity and good stability, FIPs can efficiently recognize and detect veterinary drug molecules in complex sample environments (meat products, animal blood, urine, and feces) to cope with a variety of adverse factors. Therefore, the veterinary drug residue analysis method based on MIFs demonstrate higher sensitivity and selectivity.",
